Some Palli Poligars have very high-sounding names, such as Agni
Kudirai Eriya R      ya R      vutha Minda Nainar, i.e., Nainar
who conquered R      ya R      vutha and mounted a fire horse. This
name is said to commemorate a contest between a Palli and a
R      vutha, at which the former sat on a red-hot metal horse. Further
names are S      midurai Surappa Sozhaganar and Anj      da Singam
(fearless lion). Some Pallis have adopted Gupta as a title.
A few Palli families now maintain a temple of their own, dedicated
to Sr      niv      sa, at the village of Kumalam in the South Arcot
district, live round the temple, and are largely dependent on it for
their livelihood. Most of them dress exactly like the temple Battars,
and a stranger would certainly take them for Battar Br      hmans. Some
of them are well versed in the temple ritual, and their youths are
being taught the Sandyavandhana (morning prayer) and V      das by a
Br      hman priest. Ordinary Palli girls are taken by them in
marriage, but their own girls are not allowed to marry ordinary Pallis;
and, as a result of this practice of hypergamy, the Kumalam men
sometimes have to take to themselves more than one wife, in order that
their young women may be provided with husbands. These Kumalam Pallis
are regarded as priests of the Pallis, and style themselves
K      vilar, or temple people. But, by other castes, they are
nicknamed Kumalam Br      hmans. They claim to be Kshatriyas, and have
adopted the title R      yar. [<a id="pb14" href=
"#pb14" name="pb14">14]
Other titles,        indicating authority, bravery, and
superiority,        assumed by Pallis are N      yakar, Varma,
Padaiy      chi (head of an army), Kandar, Ch      ra, Ch      la,
P      ndya, Nayanar, Udaiyar, Sambur      yar, etc.<a class="noteref"
id="xd21e572src" href="#xd21e572" name="xd21e572src">17 Still
further titles are Pillai, Reddi, Goundan, and Kavandan. Some say that
they belong to the Ch      la race, and that, as such, they should be
called Chembians.<a class="noteref" id="xd21e575src" href="#xd21e575"
name="xd21e575src">18 Iranya Varma, the name of one of the early
Pallava kings, was returned as their caste by certain wealthy Pallis,
who also gave themselves the title of S      lakanar (descendant of
Ch      la kings) at the census, 1901.
In reply to a question by the Census Superintendent, 1891, as to the
names of the sub-divisions of the caste, it was stated that        the
Vanniyans are either of the solar and lunar or Agnikula race, or Ruthra
Vanniyar, Krishna Vanniyar, Samboo Vanniyar, Brahma Vanniyar, and Indra
Vanniyar.        The most important of the sub-divisions returned at
the census were Agamudaiyan, Agni, Arasu (R      ja), Kshatriya,
N      gavadam (cobra       s hood, or ear ornament of that shape),
Nattam      n,       lai (palm leaf), Pandamuttu, and Perum      l
g      tra. Pandamuttu is made by Winslow to mean torches arranged so
