       Dr. H. H. Wilson<a class="noteref" id="xd21e1006src" href=
"#xd21e1006" name="xd21e1006src">34 is of opinion that the word
Pand      ram is        more properly P      nduranga, pale
complexioned, from their smearing themselves with ashes. It is so used
in H      machandr             s history of Mah      v      ra, when
speaking of the Saiva Br      hmans.        A more popular derivation
of the name is from Band      ram, a public treasury. A good many
well-to-do Pand      rams are managers of Siva temples in Southern
India, and accordingly have the temple treasuries under their care. It
is, however, possible that the name has been acquired by the caste by
reason of their keeping a yellow powder, called pand      ram, in a
little box, and giving it in return for the alms which they
receive.
Opinions are divided as to whether the Pand      rams are
Ling      yats or not. The opinion held by F. W. Ellis, the well-known
Tamil scholar and translator of the Kural of Tiruvalluvar, is thus
summarised by Colonel Wilks.<a class="noteref" id="xd21e1011src" href=
"#xd21e1011" name="xd21e1011src">35        Mr. Ellis considers the
Jangam of the upper countries, and the Pand      ram of the lower, to
be of the same sect, and both deny in the most unequivocal terms the
doctrine of the metempsychosis. A manuscript in the Mackenzie
collection ascribes the origin of the Pand      rams as a <span class=
"pagenum">[<a id="pb48" href="#pb48" name=
"pb48">48]sacerdotal order of the servile caste to the
religious disputes, which terminated in the suppression of the Jain
religion in the P      ndian (Madura) kingdom, and the influence which
they attained by the aid which they rendered to the Br      hmans in
that controversy, but this origin seems to require confirmation. In a
large portion, perhaps in the whole of the Br      hmanical temples
dedicated to Siva in the provinces of Arcot, Tanjore, Trichinopoly,
Madura and Tinnevelly, the Pand      ram is the highest of the temple,
and has the entire direction of the revenues, but allows the
Br      hmans to officiate in the ceremonial part according to their
own good pleasure, as a concern altogether below his note. He has
generally the reputation of an irreproachable life, and is treated by
the Br      hmans of the temple with great reverence, while on his part
he looks with compassion at the absurd trifles which occupy their
attention. These facts seem to point to some former revolution, in
which a Jangam government obtained a superiority over the
Br      hmanical establishments, and adopted this mode of superseding
the substantial part of their authority. It is a curious instance of
the Sooder (S      dra) being the spiritual lord of the Br      hman,
and is worthy of further historical investigation.        Dr.
Wilson<a class="noteref" id="xd21e1016src" href="#xd21e1016" name=
"xd21e1016src">36 also thinks that the Pand      rams are
Ling      yats. Mr. H. A. Stuart<a class="noteref" id="xd21e1020src"
href="#xd21e1020" name="xd21e1020src">37 says that they are a class
of priests who serve the non-Br      hman castes. They have returned
115 sub-divisions, of which only two are sufficiently large to require
mention,       ndi of Tinnevelly and Malabar, and Lingad      ri of
Chingleput and Tinnevelly.       ndi is a quasi-caste of beggars
recruited from all castes, and the Lingad      ri Pand      rams are
the same as Jangams. [<a id="pb49" href="#pb49"
name="pb49">49]Pand      ram is, in fact, a class name
rather than the name of a caste, and it consists of priests and
beggars. Mr. C. P. Brown<a class="noteref" id="xd21e1026src" href=
"#xd21e1026" name="xd21e1026src">38 thinks that the Pand      rams
are not Ling      yats.        The Saiva worshippers among the Tamils
are called Pand      rams: these are not Vira Saivas, nor do they wear
the linga or adore Basava. I name them here chiefly because they are
often mentioned as being Vira Saivas, whereas in truth they are (like
the Smartas) Purva Saivas, and worship the image of Siva in their
houses.        It must be remarked that Mr. Brown appears to have had a
confused idea of Pand      rams. Pand      rams wear the linga on their
bodies in one of the usual modes, are priests to others professing the
Ling      yat religion, and are fed by them on funeral and other
ceremonial occasions. At the same time, it must be added that they
are       more especially the begging sections       very lax as
regards their food and drink. This characteristic distinguishes them
from the more orthodox Ling      yats. Moreover, Ling      yats remarry
their widows, whereas the Pand      rams, as a caste, will not.
       Pand      rams speak Tamil. They are of two classes, the
married and celibate. The former are far more numerous than the latter,
and dress in the usual Hindu manner. They have the hind-lock of hair
known as the kudumi, put on sacred ashes, and paint the point between
the eyebrows with a sandal paste dot. The celibates wear orange-tawny
cloths, and daub sacred ashes all over their bodies. They allow the
hair of the head to become matted. They wear sandals with iron spikes,
and carry in their hands an iron tris      lam (the emblem of Siva),
and a wooden baton called dand      yudha (another emblem of Siva).
When they go about the [<a id="pb50" href="#pb50"
name="pb50">50]streets, they sing popular Tamil hymns, and
beat against their begging bowl an iron chain tied by a hole to one of
its sides. Married men also beg, but only use a bell-metal gong and a
wooden mallet. Most of these help pilgrims going to the more famous
Siva temples in the Madras Presidency, e.g., Tirutani, Palni,
Tiruv      nn      malai, or Tirupparankunram. Among both sections, the
dead are buried in the sitting posture, as among other Ling      yats.
A sam      dhi is erected over the spot where they are buried. This
consists of a linga and bull in miniature, which are worshipped as
often as may be found convenient.
       The managers of temples and mutts (religious institutions),
known as Pand      ra Sannadhis, belong to the celibate class. They are
usually learned in the       gamas and Pur      nas. A good many of
them are Tamil scholars, and well versed in Saiva Siddh      nta
philosophy. They call themselves Tambir      ns       a title which is
often usurped by the uneducated beggars.       
In the Census Report, 1901, Vair      vi is returned as a sub-caste
of Pand      ram, and said to be found only in the Tinnevelly district,
where they are measurers of grains and p      j      ris in village
temples. Vair      vi is further used as a name for members of the
M      lakk      ran caste, who officiate as servants at the temples of
the N      ttuk      ttai Chettis.
Pand      ram is a title of the Panisavans and Valluvan priests of
the Paraiyans.
A class of people called hill Pand      rams are described<a class=
"noteref" id="xd21e1044src" href="#xd21e1044" name=
"xd21e1044src">39 by the Rev. S. Mateer as        miserable beings
without clothing, implements, or huts of any kind, living in holes,
rocks, or trees. They bring wax, ivory (tusks), and other <span class=
"pagenum">[51]produce
to the Arayans, and get salt from them. They dig roots, snare the ibex
(wild goat, Hemitragus hylocrius) of the hills, and jungle
fowls, eat rats and snakes, and even crocodiles found in the pools
among the hill streams. They were perfectly naked and filthy, and very
timid. They spoke Malay      lam in a curious tone, and said that
twenty-two of their party had been devoured by tigers within two
monsoons.        Concerning these hill Pand      rams, Mr. N. Subramani
Aiyar writes that they live on the banks of streams in crevices of
rocks, caves, and hollows of trees. They are known to the dwellers on
the plains as K      ttumanushyar, or forest men. They clad themselves
in the bark of trees, and, in the rainy and cold seasons, protect their
bodies with plantain leaves. They speak a corrupt form of Tamil. They
fear the sight of other men, and try to avoid approaching them. A
former European magistrate of the Cardamom Hills took some of them to
his residence, but, during their three days        stay there, they
refused to eat or talk. There is a chieftain for every four hills, but
his authority is little more than nominal. When women are married, the
earth and hills are invoked as witnesses. They have Hindu names, such
as R      man, Kittan (Krishna), and Govindan.
In a lecture delivered some years ago at Trivandrum, Mr. O. H.
Bensley described the hill Pand      rams as being        skilful in
catching fish, their mode of cooking which is to place the fish on
roots on a rock, and cover them with fire. They keep dogs, and, by
their aid, replenish their larder with rats, mungooses, iguanas
(lizard, Varanus), and other delicacies. I was told that the
authority recognised by these people is the head Arayan, to whom they
give a yearly offering of jungle produce, receiving in exchange the
scanty clothing required by them. We had an opportunity of examining
their stock-in-trade, [<a id="pb52" href="#pb52"
name="pb52">52]which consisted of a bill-hook similar to
those used by other hillmen, a few earthen cooking-pots, and a good
stock of white flour, which was, they said, obtained from the bark of a
tree, the name of which sounded like       hlum. They were all small in
stature, with the exception of one young woman, and, both in appearance
and intelligence, compared favourably with the Ur      lis.       
Pand      riyar.       Pand      riyar or Pand      rattar,
denoting custodians of the treasury, has been returned as a title of
Nattam      n, Malaim      n, and Sudarm      n.
P      ndava-kulam.       A title, indicative        of the
caste of the P      ndava kings,        assumed by J      tapus and
Konda Doras, who worship the P      ndavas. The P      ndava kings were
the heroes of the Mah      bh      rata, who fought a great battle with
the Kauravas, and are said to have belonged to the lunar race of
Kshatriyas. The P      ndavas had a single wife named Draupadi, whom
the Pallis or Vanniyans worship, and celebrate annually in her honour a
fire-walking festival. The Pallis claim to belong to the fire race of
Kshatriyas, and style themselves Agnikula Kshatriyas, or Vannikula
Kshatriyas.
Pandi (pig).       Recorded as an exogamous sept of Asili,
B      ya, and Gamalla. Pandipattu (pig catchers) and Pandikottu (pig
killers) occur as exogamous septs of Odd      .
Pandito.       Pandit or Pundit (pandita, a learned man) has
been defined<a class="noteref" id="xd21e1076src" href="#xd21e1076"
name="xd21e1076src">40 as        properly a man learned in Sanskrit
lore. The Pundit of the Supreme Court was a Hindu law-officer, whose
duty it was to advise the English Judges when needful on questions of
Hindu law. The office became extinct on the constitution of the High
Court (in 1862). In the Mahratta and Telugu <span class=
"pagenum">[<a id="pb53" href="#pb53" name=
"pb53">53]countries, the word Pandit is usually pronounced
Pant (in English colloquial Punt).        In the countries noted, Pant
occurs widely as a title of Br      hmans, who are also referred to as
Pantulu v      ru. The titles Sanskrit Pundit, Telugu Pundit, etc., are
still officially recognised at several colleges in the Madras
Presidency. Pandit sometimes occurs as an honorific prefix,
e.g., Pandit S. M. Natesa Sastri, and Panditan is a name given
to Tamil barbers (Ambattan). In some parts of the Tamil country,
Panditar is used as a name for M      dhva Br      hmans, because, it
is said, many of them were formerly engaged as pandits at the Law
Courts.
Pandito is further the name of        an Oriya caste of astrologers
and physicians. They wear the sacred thread, and accept drinking water
only from Br      hmans and Gaudos. Infant marriage is practiced, and
widow marriage is prohibited.       <a class="noteref" id=
"xd21e1086src" href="#xd21e1086" name="xd21e1086src">41 I am
informed that these Panditos engage Br      hmans for their
ceremonials, do not drink liquor, and eat fish and mutton, but not
fowls or beef. The females wear glass bangles. They are known by the
name of Khodik      ro, from khodi, a kind of stone, with which they
write figures on the floor, when making astrological calculations. The
stone is said to be something like soapstone.
Pandita occurs as an exogamous sept of St      nikas.
P      ndya.       The territorial name P      ndya,
P      ndiya, P      ndiyan, or P      ndi has been returned, at recent
