Patv      g      ra.       The Patv      g      ras or
Patt      g      ras (pattu, silk) of South Canara are described by Mr.
H. A. Stuart<a class="noteref" id="xd21e2680src" href="#xd21e2680"
name="xd21e2680src">95 as        a Canarese caste of silk weavers.
They are Hindus, and worship both Siva and Vishnu, but their special
deity is Durga Param      svari at Bark      r. They wear the sacred
thread, and employ Br      hmans for ceremonial purposes. They are
governed by a body called the ten men, and pay allegiance to the guru
of the R      machandra math (religious institution). They are divided
into balis (septs) and a man may not marry within his own bali.
Polygamy is allowed only when a [<a id="pb189"
href="#pb189" name="pb189">189]wife is barren, or suffers
from some incurable disease, such as leprosy. The girls are married in
infancy, and the binding portion of the ceremony is called dh      re
(see Bant). Widow marriage is not permitted, and divorce is only
allowed in the case of an adulterous wife. They follow the ordinary
Hindu law of inheritance. The dead are cremated. The sr      dha
(memorial) ceremony is in use, and the Mah      laya ceremony for the
propitiation of ancestors in general is performed annually. Female
ancestors are also worshipped every year at a ceremony called vaddap,
when meals are given to married women. They eat fish but not meat, and
the use of alcohol is not permitted.       
In the Mysore Census Report, 1891, the Patv      g      rs are
described as        silk weavers who speak a corrupt Mar      thi
conglomerate of Guzar      ti and Hindi. They worship all the Hindu
deities, especially the female energy under the name of S      kti, to
which a goat is sacrificed on the night of the Dasara festival, a
Musalman slaughtering the animal. After the sacrifice, the family of
the Patv      g      r partake of the flesh. Many of their females are
naturally fair and handsome, but lose their beauty from early marriage
and precocity.        A few Patt      g      ras, who speak a corrupt
form of Mar      thi, are to be found in the Anantapur district.
